1.	Repository:
1.1.	What is a Repository?
•	A repository (repo) is a storage location for project files and Git history.
•	Contains source code, commits, branches, and version history
            1.2.Initialize a Repository
•	Create a Git repository: git init
•	Check repository status: git status
2.	Committing Changes:
2.1 Git add: Moves changes from working directory to staging area.
•	Command: git add filename or git add .
2.2 Git Commit: Saves staged changes permanently in local repositories.
•	Command: git commit -m “message”
2.3 Commit messages: Message should be in detail about what changes you have made
Git workflow:
Working directory->  git add -> Staging area -> git commit -> local repository
3.	Branching and Merging
3.1 What is branch?
•	A Git branch is a safe, parallel workspace used to develop features without affecting the main code.
•	View branch: git branch
3.2 Create Branches
•	Create a branch: git branch branch_name
•	Create and switch:  git switch -c branch_name or git checkout -b branch_name
•	Switch branch: git switch branch_name or git checkout branch_name
3.3 Merge Changes into Main Branch
•	Merging in git refers to combining the commit history and changes of two differ branches into one branch.
•	Switch to main branch: git switch main
•	Merge branch: git merge branch_name
•	Delete merged branch: git branch -d branch_name
